      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soak the dates",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour the boiling water over the chopped dates and bicarbonate of soda. Leave for 10 minutes, then blend or mash to a rough purée. The bicarbonate colours the water dark and reacts with the dates' acids; this is correct.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sponge",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 180°C conventional (160°C fan). Grease and line a 30 × 20 cm baking tin. Beat the softened butter and muscovado sugar together until combined, muscovado is damp and doesn't cream as smoothly as caster sugar; 3 minutes is enough. Add the eggs one at a time, then the vanilla. Fold in the flour and baking powder, then stir in the date purée. The batter will be fairly liquid. Pour into the prepared tin.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake for 28 to 35 minutes until the top is set, feels springy when pressed gently, and a skewer through the centre comes out clean. The sponge should be a deep brown, pulling slightly away from the tin edges.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the toffee sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "While the sponge bakes, melt the butter and muscovado together in a saucepan over a medium heat. Once dissolved, add the cream and salt and bring to a gentle bubble. Simmer for 3 minutes until slightly thickened. Keep warm.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sauce and serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour half the warm toffee sauce over the hot sponge as soon as it comes from the oven. Leave to soak for 5 minutes, then cut into squares and serve with the remaining sauce. Offer cream or vanilla ice cream alongside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
